  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/pull/3132",
  "title": "feat(highlight): implement InstantSearch.css",
  "body": "This PR add functionalities to highlight hits without manipulating the Algolia response object (`_highlightResult`). It provides two ways to highlight a hit.\r\n\r\n## Specs\r\n\r\n[See specs →](https://instantsearch-css.netlify.com/widgets/highlight/)\r\n\r\nNote that I didn't add the CSS class `ais-Highlight-nonHighlighted` because it complexifies the parsing for not much added value. This is also what we did for Vue InstantSearch.\r\n\r\n## API\r\n\r\n### As a function\r\n\r\nThe hit must be explicitly passed to the helper function to retrieve the highlighted value.\r\n\r\n```js\r\ninstantsearch.highlight({ attribute, highlightedTagName, hit })\r\n// => <mark class=\"ais-Highlight-highlighted\">Amazon</mark> - Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote - Black\r\n```\r\n\r\n### As a Hogan template helper\r\n\r\nThe hit is injected leveraging the `data` prop from the `Template` component, allowing to omit the `hit` parameter when using the Hogan template. The parameters are forwarded to the `highlight()` function.\r\n\r\n```js\r\n{{#highlight}}{ \"attribute\": \"name\", \"highlightedTagName\": \"mark\" }{{/highlight}}\r\n// => <mark class=\"ais-Highlight-highlighted\">Amazon</mark> - Fire TV Stick with Alexa Voice Remote - Black\r\n```\r\n\r\nIf the given object is not parsable with `JSON.parse()`, we return an empty string.\r\n\r\n## Stories\r\n\r\n- [Function](https://deploy-preview-3132--algolia-instantsearch.netlify.com/v2/dev-novel/?selectedStory=Hits.with%20highlight%20function)\r\n- [Helper](https://deploy-preview-3132--algolia-instantsearch.netlify.com/v2/dev-novel/?selectedStory=Hits.with%20highlight%20helper)",
